SIMPLE: matriculate
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Matriculate
<hw>Ma*tric"u*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Matriculated</conjf>
<pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Matriculating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>matricula</ets> a
public roll or register, dim. of <ets>matrix</ets> a mother, in respect
to propagation, also, a public register. See <er>Matrix</er>.]</ety>
<def>To enroll; to enter in a register;</def>
<specif>specifically,</specif> <def>to enter or admit to membership in a
body or society, particularly in a college or university, by enrolling
the name in a register.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In discovering and <qex>matriculating</qex> the arms of
commissaries from North America.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matriculate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Matriculate
<hw>Ma*tric"u*late</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To go though the process
of admission to membership, as by examination and enrollment, in a
society or college.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matriculate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Matriculate
<hw>Ma*tric"u*late</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<def>Matriculated.</def> <au>Skelton.</au> -- <def2><pos>n.</pos>
<def>One who is matriculated.</def></def2>
<rj><au>Arbuthnot.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Matriculation</ent>⟦br⟧
